Communicating findings from the exploration of the prosper loan dataset¶

by Olamide Olowoniyi

Preliminary wrangling¶

The prosper loan data set contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and so many others.

What is the structure of the dataset?¶

From the quick assessment of the data done above, the results showed that the dataset contained 81 columns and 113,937 rows, that is, 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in this dataset?¶

I am majorly interested in the factors or variables that determine a loan's interest rate.

What features in the dataset will help support investigation into the feature(s) of interest?¶

I suspect that there are a couple of features in the dataset responsible for deteminining a loan's interest rate. These include: The Borrower's APR, Prosperscore, Creditscore and DebtToIncomeRatio.

Univariate exploration¶

I will start this section investigating the distribution of credit scores among borrowers. Credit score is believed to be an imporant factor in determining whether a borrower is loan worthy or not.

In [16]:
#plotting histogram to check the distribution of credit scores of borrowers
plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))

plt.title("Distribution of Borrowers' Credit Score (lower range)")

plt.ylabel('Number of Listings')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

plt.figure(figsize=(8,8))
sb.countplot(data = loan_target, x = 'CreditScoreRangeUpper', color = 'blue')
plt.title("Distribution of Borrowers' Credit Score (upper range)")
plt.xlabel('Credit Score Range (Upper)')
plt.ylabel('Number of Listings')
plt.xticks(rotation=90);

The upper and lower range plots look similar and they both look like a normally distributed data. From the plots, a lot of the borrowers are having credit scores between 600 and 800. The mode of the distribution of the lower range falls around 680 while the upper range falls around 699. While different lenders have different ideas of what they consider acceptable credit score, generally a good credit score is betweet 670 and 639. this is where a considerable number of our borrowers lie.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?

My unvariate exploration provided a good first insight into the prosper loan data sight. Howefver, I found that some of my variables of interest do not necessariily agree with each other. the data showed that the ethe borrowers had fairly good credit scores, their debt to income ratio was also good, their stated monthly income levels and monthly loan payments were such that they should be able to pay without too much stress, evein their revolvong credit balance seemed good. However, the the borrower's APR and prosper scores seemed to tell a different stories implying that the borrowers were taking out high riisk loans or my be in some kind of financial trouble. Even the listing categories semmed to agree with this as most of the loans the borrowers took out fell under the debt conolidation catergory i.e. to pay off other debts.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?

Some of the variables I investigated had outliers in their data, so I had to clean the data to improve the accuracy of my analysis. Some of the data cleaning conducted are:

  1. Removing all stated monthly income above 25,000
  2. Removing al revolving credit balances above 90,000
  3. Removing debt to income ratio above 1
  4. Removing monthy loan payments ablove 700
  5. Changing the listing numeric data type to category datatype
  6. Changing column name of the listing cateory variable

Bivariate Exploration¶

This section of the analysis will be used to investigate relationships between pairs of variable of interest to get better insights.

First, I will begin with a correlation matrix to find out if any variables are highly correlated

In [47]:
num_vars = ['BorrowerAPR', 'ProsperScore',  'Term', 'StatedMonthlyIncome', 'MonthlyLoanPayment', 'DebtToIncomeRatio', 
            'RevolvingCreditBalance', 'CreditScoreRangeUpper', 'CreditScoreRangeLower',]

plt.figure(figsize = [8, 8])
sb.heatmap(loan_target[num_vars].corr(), annot = True, fmt = '.3f',
           cmap = 'vlag_r', center = 0)
plt.title('Correlation Plot') 
plt.show()

I do not see a clear positive relationship between any pairs. It can be assumed that the relationship between BorrowerAPR and ProsperScore are negatively correlated because borrowers with lower scores are more likely to pay higher APR.

let's take a futher look at the relationship between the borrower APR and the prosper score next

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?

  1. I observed that Prosper Score and Borrower APR have a strong correlation, where the higher the prosper score, the lower the APR. This was not surprising at all, as prosper score is an independent variable designed as a custom risk score using historical Data.

  2. Similarly, there was also a strong correlation between the credit scores of borrowers and the APR. This is expected, as generally people with good credit scores are deemed reliable and loan worthy.

  3. I also observed a slight correlation between the stated monthly income and the monthly loan payment, where the higher the income level, the higher the loan payments.

  4. The correlation between stated monthly income and Debt to income ratio was a lot clearer, here, the lessser the income level, the higher the debt to income ratio; implying that people with lowr incomes take on more loans or have more debts to pay.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest?

I observed that there was very little correlation between the loan APR and the borrower's employment status. Here, you have borrower's that are unemployed having lower APR on their loans than an employed person. I found this really strange and rather interesting. What could have driven that decision?

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?

I decided to combine the Credit Score, Prosper score and BorrowerAPR because these values showed the strongest correlation with one another. The plot showed that credit score was a big factor in in determining a loan's APR and it also showed that it is possible for with credit scores around 700 to have have great prosper scores like 10. This grants borrowers with these scores access to loans with even lower interest rates which may not have been possible if they were considered solely on their credit scores.

Plotting these three variables together stregthened the analysis for me to see this insight in this way.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

Of course, the addition of the loan terms to the exploration provided even more insight. We could see that there are more borrowers with lower credit scores opting for the 36 month loans. Same thing applies for the prosper loan data, with more borrowers opting for the 36 term loans and these borrowers were observed to have lower prosper scores credit scores than the other borrowers.
